{"key":"post-12770889","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12770889</id>\n<content>That's a method that will fail with straw more than it succeeds.&amp;nbsp; You can use a stove to heat the water, but pour it into a container and let it cool down to about 170F before adding the straw.&amp;nbsp; If you sterilize the straw, it's more likely to contaminate.&amp;nbsp; You want to preserve the beneficial bacteria, so don't subject it to boiling temp water.&amp;nbsp; Follow the video posted above.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The dish soap is a wetting agent.&amp;nbsp; It helps the straw to hydrate in two hours rather than soaking it 24 hours before pasteurizing.&amp;nbsp; It also helps to kill some of the bacteria and most of the mold spores.&amp;nbsp; Some growers in third world countries use soap-only pasteurization, but they also have a high contamination rate.&amp;nbsp; However, if they don't have access to electricity, gas, or wood to heat the water, it's one method to get by with.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12771075</next>\n<prev>12770675</prev>\n<first>12770491</first>\n<last>12848251</last>\n<when>1277002081</when>\n<utime>06/20/10 05:48 AM</utime>\n</post>"}